^ ryezensun. "Re: eBay Global Shipping Program ...". eBay Seller Central forum. Retrieved March 10, 2017. The one part I don't like ... is, lately, they keep bringing up the user agreement when I log in, wanting me to accept their rules and regulations. Now, they know most people will not actually read it all, and [will] just scroll to the bottom and press 'I accept'. The new GSP is in there, and if you 'accept' at the bottom of the page, you accept it all, and now your automatically enrolled in the GSP. A lot of seller's don't even realize this. One seller said 'it must have been something I did', as she said she definitely did not, and would not sign up for it. I suspect she clicked the 'I accept' button, having no idea. And by the way, there are no options in that form to exclude the GSP. Very, very smart, eBay. 
^ pjcdn2005 (February 8, 2013). "Re: eBay Global shipping program". eBay Seller Central forum. Post 13. Retrieved May 1, 2013. 
^ In theory, on incoming packages worth Can$20 or more, the Canadian postal service is always supposed to charge customs duty, taxes, and/or customs-clearance fees: see [1]. In practice, these charges are usually only applied to express mail, not to first-class mail or priority mail.[2] Unfortunately, the operators of the Global Shipping Program are much stricter than the Canadian postal service. Whenever any item worth Can$20 or more is delivered to Canada, even by first-class mail, the operators of the Global Shipping Program always charge customs duty, taxes, and/or customs-clearance fees: see [3]. This can considerably increase Canadian buyers' costs on items worth Can$20 or more: see [4].
